{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"45865170-d27a-4694-bd3c-d1fb35683c71","content":"Good questions — let me clarify both.\n\n**`ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"True\"`** — ✅ Correct. This is the standard iOS platform-specific attached property in .NET MAUI. It automatically adds padding to keep content within the safe area (away from the notch/Dynamic Island). Usage:\n\n```xml\n<ContentPage\n    xmlns:ios=\"clr-namespace:Microsoft.Maui.Controls.PlatformConfiguration.iOSSpecific;assembly=Microsoft.Maui.Controls\"\n    ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"True\">\n```\n\n**`IgnoreSafeArea=\"True\"` on a Grid** — ❌ Not a real .NET MAUI property. That tutorial is likely outdated or incorrect.\n\n### Background image pattern\n\nFor a full-bleed background image with safe content, **don't** use `UseSafeArea` on the page. Instead, layer manually:\n\n```xml\n<ContentPage xmlns:ios=\"...\">\n    <!-- Don't set UseSafeArea here -->\n    <Grid>\n        <!-- Layer 0: full-bleed background -->\n        <Image Source=\"bg.png\" Aspect=\"AspectFill\" />\n\n        <!-- Layer 1: safe content with manual padding -->\n        <StackLayout Padding=\"{OnPlatform iOS='20,60,20,34'}\"\n                     VerticalOptions=\"Fill\">\n            <Label Text=\"Hello, safe area!\" />\n        </StackLayout>\n    </Grid>\n</ContentPage>\n```\n\nOr, for dynamic safe area insets, use `On<iOS>().SafeAreaInsets()` in code-behind to read the actual insets and apply them to your content layer programmatically.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"1a8dcf8c-ec18-4974-a266-b16a5d4fa08e","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about .NET MAUI safe area handling on iOS, specifically about two properties:\n\n1. `ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"True\"` - a platform-specific property for ContentPage\n2. `IgnoreSafeArea=\"True\"` - a property on Grid for background images\n\nLet me check what I know about these APIs in .NET MAUI, particularly for .NET 10.\n\nIn .NET MAUI, the iOS safe area handling has evolved:\n\n1. `ios:Page.UseSafeArea` - This is a platform-specific API from `Microsoft.Maui.Controls.PlatformConfiguration.iOSSpecific`. It was available in earlier versions of .NET MAUI. In XAML, you'd use it with the `xmlns:ios` namespace.\n\n\n2. For .NET 9 and beyond, there have been changes to how safe areas are handled. The `ios:Page.UseSafeArea` property is still valid as an iOS platform-specific, but `IgnoreSafeArea` isn't a standard .NET MAUI property—that's likely something custom or from a different framework.\n\nI should be clear about what I'm confident in: `UseSafeArea` comes from `Microsoft.Maui.Controls.PlatformConfiguration.iOSSpecific` and has been available since early .NET MAUI versions, but I'm less certain about the exact state of these APIs in .NET 10 specifically. For individual views in .NET MAUI, there isn't a direct `IgnoreSafeArea` property to opt out of safe area handling. The better approach is to either disable `UseSafeArea` on the page entirely and manually add padding where needed, or use an AbsoluteLayout where the background image spans the full page while content sits in a separate layer with safe area padding applied.","outputTokens":1515,"requestId":"E834:1A9E4C:2685D0B:2AB9320:69F94393"},"id":"dc3c99e3-36f3-4862-8438-4582005f0d91","timestamp":"2026-05-05T01:11:13.351Z","parentId":"0694eb18-cd92-4770-8ee0-44e1241a47c5"}
